          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><p><em>将精彩的阅读推荐发送到您的收件箱。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/newsletters?sub=410&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">订阅</a>每周的图书时事通讯。</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 04 Aug 2023 18:09:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-ec01d24e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-ec01d24e<category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Founders Anticipated the Threat of Trump]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>本周对前总统的起诉书概述了宪法制定者最担心的对法治的煽动性挑战<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829528/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>佐哈尔·拉扎尔<span>佐哈尔·拉扎尔</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001107537"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001107537"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">杰弗里·罗森</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 4 日下午 1:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-founders-anticipated-the-threat-of-trump-becda1b"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">唐纳德·特朗普 (Donald Trump)</a>被指控密谋推翻 2020 年大选，这是美国开国元勋们的噩梦。詹姆斯·麦迪逊和亚历山大·汉密尔顿的一个主要担忧是，煽动者会煽动暴徒和派别藐视法治，推翻自由和公平的选举，破坏美国民主。亚历山大·汉密尔顿 (Alexander Hamilton) 在 1790 年写道：“颠覆国家共和制度的唯一途径就是迎合人民的偏见，激起他们的嫉妒和忧虑，使事情陷入混乱，引发民众骚乱。”汉密尔顿警告说：“当一个私生活中无原则、对财富绝望、脾气暴躁的人……被认为骑上了受欢迎的木马时，他可能会‘乘风破浪，引领旋风’。”</p><p>国父们设计了一个宪法制度，正是为了防止煽动者以这种方式散布混乱和暴民暴力。麦迪逊说，这个国家幅员辽阔，当地派系很难协调任何形式的群众动员。政府三个部门之间权力的横向分立将确保众议院弹劾腐败总统、参议院对腐败总统定罪。州和联邦政府之间的垂直权力划分将确保地方官员确保选举的公正性。</p><p>乔治·华盛顿在两届任期后自愿下台的典范强化了和平权力移交的规范，这将确保任何民选总统都无法像凯撒那样将自己转变为未经选举产生的独裁者。汉密尔顿写道：“在这个国家引入君主制或贵族制的想法是那些有远见的事情之一，除了疯子之外没有人能想到”，只要美国人民抵制“由于政府行为而造成的动乱和混乱”。受欢迎的煽动者。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828944?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2021 年 1 月 6 日，华盛顿特区，支持特朗普的抗议者冲进美国国会大厦，试图阻止乔·拜登当选总统的选票认证。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：JT/STAR MAX/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>根据本周发布的联邦起诉书，特朗普总统试图通过一系列明知的谎言，密谋散布此类“痉挛和骚乱”，从而推翻 2020 年选举结果。起诉书称，选举日后不久，特朗普“采取非法手段削弱合法选票并颠覆选举结果”，实施了三项不同的犯罪阴谋：阻碍选票的收集和计票、国会于 1 月 6 日对结果的认证。 ，2021年，以及投票权本身。</p><p>起诉书称，这三起阴谋都涉及特朗普及其同谋利用“故意虚假的选举舞弊指控”来颠覆选举结果。特别是，特朗普据称“在七个目标州组织了欺诈性的选举人名单”；试图利用“司法部的权力和权威进行虚假选举犯罪调查”；试图招募副总统<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/mike-pence">迈克·彭斯</a>“以欺诈手段改变选举结果”；随着 1 月 6 日暴力事件爆发，他加倍努力“说服国会议员进一步推迟认证”。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="wsj-article-pullquote article__inset__pullquote "><p class="pullquote-content article__inset__pullquote__quote"> <span class="l-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--left">“</span> ‘我不相信美国历史上有任何事情能接近这一点。’” <span class="r-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--right">”</span></p> <small><span class="inset-author article__inset__pullquote__author">— J. Michael Luttig，前美国上诉法院法官</span></small></div></div><p>起诉书称，在所有这些情况下，特朗普推翻选举的阴谋都遭到有原则的州和联邦官员的抵制，其中包括亚利桑那州众议院共和党议长、他自己内阁的共和党成员以及许多一致拒绝的州和联邦法官。虚假选举指控。</p><p>起诉书的辩护者认为，面对我们的民主制度面临如此严重的威胁，特别检察官杰克·史密斯被迫寻求起诉书。 “我认为美国历史上没有任何事情可以接近这一点，”前美国上诉法院法官 J. Michael Luttig 告诉我。卢蒂格是一位受人尊敬的保守派法学家，他帮助说服副总统彭斯相信他没有权力推翻选举结果。他说：“这些是现任总统可能对美国犯下的最严重罪行，除了可能的叛国罪。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="544" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829586?width=700&amp;height=544" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 8 月 1 日，华盛顿特区，前总统特朗普被指控密谋推翻 2020 年大选，特别检察官杰克·史密斯 (Jack Smith) 向记者发表讲话。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：比尔·奥利里/华盛顿邮报/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>相比之下，起诉书的批评者认为，即使特朗普确实试图推翻选举结果，只要他合理地相信选举被窃取，他的努力就不违法。哈佛大学法学教授艾伦·德肖维茨（Alan Dershowitz）在第一次弹劾中为特朗普辩护：“为了确定根本指控，政府必须毫无疑问地证明特朗普本人确实知道并相信他公平公正地输掉了选举。” 《每日邮报》写道，审判。 “我怀疑他们能否证明这一点。” 《国家评论》社论称，即使是虚假的政治言论也受到第一修正案的保护：“假设检察官能够毫无疑问地证明特朗普并没有真正说服自己选举被窃取（祝你好运），夸张甚至夸张更糟糕的是受保护的政治言论。”</p><p>特朗普案的一个具有启发性的历史类比是围绕 1800 年选举的言论自由和选举公正性争议，这场争议最终导致对亚伦·伯尔的叛国罪审判。选举前两年，国会中的联邦党人通过了《煽动叛乱法》，规定“撰写、印刷、发表或出版……任何虚假、诽谤性和恶意的文章或反对美国政府的文章”都是非法的。实际上，这让批评联邦党总统约翰·亚当斯成为犯罪行为，从而压制了共和党反对派的声音。</p><p>共和党副总统托马斯·杰斐逊回应称，各州有权废除他们不同意的联邦法律。在随后的选举中，亚当斯名列第三，杰斐逊和他的副总统亚伦·伯尔获得同等数量的选举人票。亚历山大·汉密尔顿认为杰斐逊对共和国的威胁小于伯尔，他帮助说服国会中的联邦党人选举杰斐逊，而国会中的联邦党人不得不打破平局。亚当斯和伯尔都接受了选举结果，并支持和平移交权力。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/2f0a5fa0-9cf5-4eba-9197-e0f194029f68.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>然而，一上任，杰斐逊就对其政敌进行了报复。他鼓励各州起诉联邦党人的批评者，并猛烈抨击他的主要竞争对手、首席大法官约翰·马歇尔。</p>他还支持弹劾大法官塞缪尔·蔡斯（Samuel Chase），一位曾主持其中一项煽动叛乱审判的党派联邦党人，但参议院宣判蔡斯无罪，开创了国会不应因为不同意法官裁决而罢免法官的先例。<p></p><p>杰斐逊随后以叛国罪起诉他的前副总统伯尔。 1804 年，在著名的决斗中杀死汉密尔顿后，伯尔向西逃亡以改善自己的命运，并组织了一支探险队，夺取德克萨斯州和路易斯安那州属于西班牙的土地。 1806 年，杰斐逊收到报告，称伯尔密谋煽动西部各州脱离联邦并征服新领土。杰斐逊通知国会并下令逮捕伯尔。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="wsj-article-pullquote article__inset__pullquote "><p class="pullquote-content article__inset__pullquote__quote"> 1800 年，<span class="l-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--left">党派</span>热情高涨，就像今天一样，但由于主要机构参与者的自我克制，美国的机构和规范得以幸存。 <span class="r-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--right">”</span></p></div></div><p>次年，伯尔的叛国罪审判由首席大法官马歇尔主持，但马歇尔对起诉书持怀疑态度。他向杰斐逊发出传票，要求他交出伯尔所说的辩护所需的文件。杰斐逊最初声称拥有行政特权，但最终移交了这些信件。马歇尔随后告诉陪审团，根据宪法，叛国罪定罪需要两名证人证明对美国实施的公开战争行为的证据，但这样的证据并不存在。陪审团很快裁定伯尔无罪。据报道，杰斐逊想就马歇尔在伯尔审判中的行为提出弹劾指控，但因蔡斯法官无罪释放所确立的先例而被阻止。</p><p>与亚伦·伯尔不同，唐纳德·特朗普并未因叛国罪被起诉。但对伯尔的审判以及围绕 1800 年选举的法律争议为美国机构在 2024 年选举前后将面临的挑战提供了教训。当时和现在一样，出现了民主衰退的严重警告信号，指控称：双方都通过党派起诉和攻击言论自由、司法独立和法治来将反对派定为犯罪。</p><p> 1800 年，党派热情高涨，就像今天一样，但美国的制度和规范得以幸存，这要归功于主要制度参与者的自我克制和他们对维护联邦的承诺。亚当斯和伯尔接受了选举结果，杰斐逊接受了伯尔的判决，共和党国会拒绝弹劾马歇尔。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828955?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">作为一名年轻的政治家，亚伯拉罕·林肯曾公开担心创始人建立的机构债券能维持多久。随着他的当选和内战的开始，他们破裂了。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Leigh Vogel/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>这种制度性的自我克制在内战前的几十年里被打破了。</p>亚伯拉罕·林肯 (Abraham Lincoln) 于 1860 年作为联邦和法治的捍卫者、反对暴民暴力的威胁参加竞选。南方各州以脱离联邦作为对他当选的回应，援引了杰斐逊在反对《煽动叛乱法》时提出的相同的州权利论点。一代人之前盛行的共同准则和宪法承诺还不足以避免战争灾难。<p></p><p>今天的重大问题是我们的领导人和公众将遵循哪些历史先例。唐纳德·特朗普 (Donald Trump) 面临一系列法律麻烦，但尽管他在 2024 年共和党提名竞选中占据主导地位，但本周宣布的起诉书影响最为深远，指控他积极破坏我们宪法秩序的基本要素。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>对唐纳德·特朗普的最新起诉对我们民主制度的力量有何评价？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>共和党人和民主党人面临的挑战将是共同捍卫法治，并让司法程序顺其自然，就像伯尔审判中所发生的那样。否则，2024 年的选举可能会演变成我们制度的悲剧性破裂，更像是 1860 年而不是 1800 年。</p><p>托马斯·杰斐逊 (Thomas Jefferson) 和约翰·亚当斯 (John Adams) 在 1800 年爆炸性选举后的十年里和解了，在生命的最后时刻，他们对美国实验的未来感到悲观。亚当斯担心美国公民缺乏足够的公民道德来维持共和国，而杰斐逊则担心奴隶制问题上的派系冲突会摧毁联邦。</p><p>在建国一代人中，只有詹姆斯·麦迪逊对美国机构的生存持适度乐观态度。他希望能够教育公众舆论来克服最具破坏性的党派激情。他相信，除其他外，一群开明的“文人”将利用印刷媒体的新技术将冷静的理性声音传播到整个国家。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829530?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">特朗普周四抵达罗纳德·里根华盛顿国家机场，接受法官关于联邦共谋指控的传讯。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：亚历克斯·布兰登/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>在我们这个两极分化的时代，麦迪逊的乐观主义现在看起来有些古怪。在社交媒体上，凭借“激怒参与”的商业模式，旨在激发我们党派热情的帖子比那些基于说服性理由的帖子传播得更远、更快。民主的透明度和参与度以开国元勋们无法想象的方式增长，扩大了早就该有的权利和自由，但也拉平了他们为促进精英深思熟虑而设置的减速带。</p><p>开国元勋们害怕直接民主，并制定了一部宪法来抑制它，这让今天的改革者感到沮丧。他们会对我们当前的政治制度感到惊讶，总统初选制度、全国性的竞选活动和日益复杂的媒体定位，所有这些都为党派极端分子和煽动者提供了新的机会。</p><p>年轻的亚伯拉罕·林肯在他最早的政治演讲之一中表达了开国元勋们对民主制度如何崩溃的担忧。当时担任伊利诺伊州立法机构成员的他担心，如果出现一位具有煽动性野心的领导人，而他不致力于建国一代建立的机构，那么共和国的命运将会如何。林肯说：“名声将是他的首要目标，尽管他也愿意，也许更愿意通过行善而不是伤害来获得它；然而，这个机会已经过去了，在建设方面也没有什么可做的了，他就会大胆地开始进行拆除的任务。”</p><p>杰弗里<em>·罗森 (Jeffrey Rosen) 是国家宪法中心的总裁兼首席执行官。他的新书《追求幸福：古典美德作家如何启发创始人的生活并定义美国》将于二月由西蒙与舒斯特出版社出版。</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 04 Aug 2023 17:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-Founders-anticipated-the-threat-of-trump-becda1b</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-Founders-anticipated-the-threat-of-trump-becda1b<category>华尔街日报评论</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>历史</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>亚伦·伯尔</category><category>唐纳德·特朗普</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>历史</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The Good Virus’ Review: An Unlikely Healer]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>噬菌体疗法在细菌上释放病毒。这种治疗可能会挽救生命。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12705823021609713873204590088620979765954"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829253?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">细菌的培养皿。清晰的斑点是噬菌体杀死细菌的区域。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：borzywoj/Alamy </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12705823021609713873204590088620979765954"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者：<span class="author" itemprop="name">大卫·A·谢维茨</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 4 日中午 12:04 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-good-virus-review-an-unlikely-healer-1eb05588"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> 2015年，加州大学圣地亚哥分校精神病学教授汤姆·帕特森在度假时爬过埃及红色金字塔的一座小坟墓后不久就病倒了。他的病情迅速恶化，首先被转移到德国法兰克福的重症监护室，然后又被转移到他位于加利福尼亚州拉霍亚的家庭医院。他病情的根本原因是感染<em>鲍曼<em>不</em>动杆菌</em><em>——</em> “最糟糕的细菌”据他的医生说。更糟糕的是，该菌株对抗生素具有抗药性。帕特森先生的妻子是一位卓有成就的全球健康流行病学家，她疯狂地在世界各地寻找任何可能有帮助的东西。她选择的治疗方法是“噬菌体”——攻击细菌的病毒。令人惊讶的是，这种疗法有效。帕特森先生从死亡边缘起死回生，最终完全康复。</p><p>在新冠病毒大流行之后，病毒有益的想法可能看起来很奇怪，甚至难以置信。但令人钦佩的是，科学记者汤姆·爱尔兰决心向我们展示这种抗击疾病的方法有多么有效，并让我们相信它的重要性。 《善良的病毒》内容丰富，引人入胜，它描述了噬菌体（通常缩写为“噬菌体”）独特的生物学和黑暗的历史，噬菌体是一种极其丰富但又晦涩难懂的生命形式，被称为“人类的暗物质”。生物学。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><p><strong>好病毒</strong></p><p><em>汤姆·爱尔兰</em></p><p><em>诺顿，389 页，30 美元</em></p></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/a315c35d-76ed-4bf8-9764-56126e52a5b3.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>噬菌体病毒无处不在，从寒冷的山区和海水到植物叶子，尤其是人体。人体 30 万亿个细胞的数量远远少于近 40 万亿个定植细菌和 10 倍数量的噬菌体，这些细菌主要存在于我们的肠道中。据估计，世界上存在数万亿种噬菌体，其中大多数尚未被发现，它们代表着“地球上遗传多样性的最大来源”，爱尔兰先生写道。</p><p>噬菌体的大小通常小于细菌细胞的十分之一。它们有多种形状，但总的来说，它们的外观和行为都像微型灯泡注射器，遗传物质（通常是 DNA，偶尔是 RNA）紧紧地盘绕在蛋白质胶囊（病毒的“头部”）内。与此同时，尾巴会抓住目标细菌，使病毒能够注入致命的有效载荷。一旦进入内部，噬菌体 DNA 就会劫持细菌机器进行自我复制，并用病毒颗粒淹没细胞，直到细菌爆裂，释放噬菌体来感染新宿主。有时，感染性 DNA 会选择低调，等待条件成熟时发起致命攻击。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-ec01d24e?mod=books_arts_lead_story" target="_blank" class="icon none">本周我们读的 14 本书</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-ec01d24e?mod=books_arts_lead_story"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828171?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p>第二修正案及其不满、奥古斯特·威尔逊的生活和戏剧、海洋深处的旅程等等。</p></div></div><p>虽然噬菌体活动的例子在历史上一直存在——例如，噬菌体可能解释了印度恒河传说中的治愈特性——但他们的发现直到 20 世纪初才被发现。爱尔兰先生写道，在这个时代，“微生物狩猎”已成为“吸引全世界关注的光鲜亮丽的职业”。 1910 年代初期，在伦敦南部的一家研究所，一丝不苟的英国细菌学家 Frederick Twort 开始在培养皿中培养天花病毒，希望它能“像细菌一样被观察和研究”。他成功地只培养了污染细菌，但在这些菌落中，他注意到偶尔出现小间隙，就好像有看不见的东西正在杀死细菌。随着第一次世界大战的爆发，特沃特失去了资金，关闭了他的实验室，并于 1915 年发表了他的研究结果，谨慎地暗示病毒可能是所观察到的现象的原因。很少有人注意到。</p><p>特沃特不太可能的竞争对手是菲利克斯·德赫雷尔 (Felix d&#39;Herelle)，一位自由奔放的法国人，他 16 岁时离开学校去环游世界，“花的是他关系密切的家庭的钱”，正如爱尔兰先生所说。 24 岁时，d&#39;Herelle 搬到了加拿大，“那里的微生物学家太少了，他干脆宣称自己是其中之一”并开设了商店。但很快他就产生了旅行的冲动，发现自己身在墨西哥，通过培养感染昆虫的细菌来帮助政府控制蝗灾。在他的职业生涯后期，在研究痢疾时，他又回到了这本剧本，寻找一种可能攻击致病细菌的“超级微生物”。他发现了与特沃特观察到的相同的玻璃斑，并（明显不那么克制）于 1917 年宣布他发现了一种新的生命形式，他称之为“噬菌体”。德赫雷尔继续使用噬菌体成功治疗了五名生病的男孩。但他的“狂野和粗鲁的风格”（用爱尔兰先生的话说）引起了他的同僚的反感，他们密谋削弱他。</p><p>德赫雷尔的发现启发了许多人，其中包括来自苏联格鲁吉亚共和国的微生物学家乔治·埃利亚瓦 (George Eliava)。 1936 年，他建立了第一个专门从事噬菌体研究的研究所（也是为数不多的研究所之一）。不幸的是，埃利亚瓦很快就与苏联秘密警察发生了冲突，后者于 1937 年失踪了他。该研究所继续致力于噬菌体疗法的开发，并取得了许多胜利——例如，噬菌体帮助治疗了患有坏疽的士兵。但也有令人沮丧的失败，部分原因是噬菌体没有充分纯化，而且通常是因为它们与感染细菌的特定菌株不适当匹配。爱尔兰先生报告说，虽然世界（包括美国）最初“为噬菌体疗法而疯狂”，但结果“不一致且不可预测”。事实上，我们了解到，20 世纪 30 年代“美国商业噬菌体产品的可疑性和不可靠性”意味着“它们是否对特定患者有效完全取决于彩票”。</p><p>第二次世界大战期间，西方果断转向新发现的青霉素，与苏联分享其配方，但不分享大规模生产方法。因此，苏联人继续依靠噬菌体作为细菌感染的首选疗法。 1949年，当一名苏联研究人员试图获得青霉素的生产权时，他被政府当局逮捕并在审讯中死亡，这一切都是因为<em>“nizkopoklonstvo”</em>罪——奉承西方。</p><p>爱尔兰先生表示，西方医生则拥护清洁且经过充分测试的抗生素，并将噬菌体视为“医学黑暗而古老的过去的遗物”。但研究人员热衷于使用噬菌体作为实验室工具，它最终揭示了分子生物学的一系列重要原理，包括识别 DNA 作为潜在的遗传物质。细菌对噬菌体的抗性研究后来揭示了独特的 DNA 序列（称为 Crispr）的存在，它可以帮助细菌通过剪断感染噬菌体的 DNA 来保护自己。后来的研究表明，科学家可以将这种分子编辑重新用于精确的基因工程。</p><p>爱尔兰先生写道，曾经“被嘲笑为怪人和共产主义者的想法”，噬菌体疗法似乎正在复兴。多年来，基于噬菌体的药物受到了全球一群真正信徒的特殊支持，现在已经吸引了强大的生物技术专家和投资者的注意。几个团队正在尝试从头开始合成药物级噬菌体；其他人正在努力使从细菌中分离噬菌体的过程系统化和标准化，并寻求监管部门对整个过程的批准。当然存在迫切的需求：爱尔兰先生提醒我们，最后一类新型抗生素是几十年前开发的，而耐药细菌的问题仍在继续加剧。经过多年的科学放逐，治疗性噬菌体也许终于可以摆脱寒冷了。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——博士。 Shaywitz 是武田制药公司的医师兼科学家、哈佛大学讲师和美国企业研究所兼职研究员。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 04 Aug 2023 16:04:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-good-virus-review-an-unlikely-healer-1eb05588</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-good-virus-review-an-unlikely-healer-1eb05588<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>健康</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>健康</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Three Books on the Second Amendment]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>一位小说家、一位教授和一位法律学者最近写的书可能会给美国关于枪支的古老争论注入新的见解——也可能不会。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590126134258415498"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829792?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：斯科特·奥尔森/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590126134258415498"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/barton-swaim" itemprop="url" rel="author">巴顿·斯威姆</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 4 日中午 12:03 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/three-books-on-the-second-amendment-a2c669e8"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>美国的枪支问题没有政治解决方案。枪支管制倡导者认为，对大规模枪击事件的正确反应是让枪支更难获得。反对者指出，数以亿计的枪支已经在流通，而随之而来的现实是，任何监管都不会改变这样一个事实：如果你想要一把枪，你就可以得到一把;因此他们甚至抵制最温和的限制。整个争论（如果这个词合适的话）自 20 世纪 90 年代中期以来一直陈旧且重复。</p><p>小说家保罗·奥斯特在《血腥国家》中似乎瞬间意识到，要对这个国家过去 30 或 40 年来武装疯子连续发生的噩梦般的大规模谋杀说一些原创或有用的东西，需要作家超越政府解决方案。他写道：“我们作为一个国家面临的巨大问题不可能通过颁布新法律或废除旧法律或通过国会推动创新安全措施来解决。” “零碎的立法可能有助于减轻一些损害，但永远无法触及问题的核心。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/4fc6acbd-4a4b-4ab7-bcb3-c1a6062e58f6.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>问题的核心是什么？答案从来没有我希望的那么明确，它似乎要求我们——“我们”指的是美国人——认真思考由拥有枪支的人所犯下的许多大规模谋杀行为。为此，奥斯特先生以可怕的细节描述了其中一些行为，并在文字中穿插了这些地点的照片。 （这些图像是颗粒状的、黑白的，而且制作起来并不令人印象深刻。）作者似乎在说，当我们沉浸在这一切的恐怖之中之后，我们就会想出一个解决方案。</p><p>奥斯特先生很像 2013 年出版的 Kindle 单曲《枪》中的恐怖小说作家斯蒂芬·金 (Stephen King)，他的写作就好像小说家所表现出的道德厌恶和愤怒能够以某种方式让每个人都清醒过来。当然，很少有读者在读著名左翼奥斯特先生关于枪支的书时需要被说服接受他在这个问题上的观点，因此这本书常常让人感觉像是一种徒劳的暴露癖练习。</p><p>一方面，它充满了作者认为深刻的似是而非的论点。例如：随着时间的推移，汽车变得越来越安全，枪支也可能变得越来越安全。 “毫无疑问，”他写道，“汽车与枪支并没有太大不同。一把大威力自动步枪和一辆四千磅重的雪佛兰在高速公路上疾驰。 。 。都是致命武器。”他认为，这种比较“引出了一个问题：如果我们能够直面汽车带来的危险，并运用我们的大脑和共同目标感来应对这些危险，为什么我们不能用枪支做同样的事情呢？ ” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/c7374fb0-29c8-454a-ab97-e17d32258fd3.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>这种比较有很多错误——汽车并不是被设计成武器的，汽车上的任何安全功能都不会阻止你用它杀人，如果你想的话。但相关的一点是，几十年来枪支<em>已经</em>受到监管并变得更加安全。另外——请原谅我的无礼——但是哪个小说家在写“不要犯错误”时，在他的意思是“提出问题”时使用“回避问题”？</p><p>在某些方面，奥斯特先生似乎遵循了我所认为的他的本能观点，即他所描述的恐怖不仅仅源于枪支的可用性。 “贯穿所有[肇事者]故事的一个词就是<em>孤独</em>，”他写道，“难以忍受、令人心碎的孤独。”这是真的。但这让我想知道为什么奥斯特先生不写一本关于孤独的书，这个主题还没有被无休止地写出来和喋喋不休，而是写枪，而枪已经被写了。然而，到了书的结尾，这一切又都是枪支的错：“人们用枪射击别人，因为他们有枪。”</p><p>对最后声明中表达的观点表示怀疑并不是否认枪支工业最近养成了一些恶意的惯例。作为一个在充满优质左轮手枪和霰弹枪的家庭中长大的枪主，看着一把带有手枪式握把和一个大的突出弹匣的黑色半自动步枪，并询问它是否还有其他用途，这并不是没有道理的。比杀人。这些凶猛武器的流行在一定程度上是一种政治观点的表达——可以说，这种观点有其愤世嫉俗和虚无主义的一面。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/7fed5401-f466-4189-9a06-5fa63e467008.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>亚利桑那大学社会学和公共政策副教授詹妮弗·卡尔森（Jennifer Carlson）试图在《右翼商人：枪支销售商与美国民主危机》中描述这种政治观点。你可以通过其灾难性的标题猜出这本书的主旨，但卡尔森女士的前提——夫妻枪支商店已经成为政治辩论的小舞台——有一定的吸引力。 “枪支商店与十九世纪的咖啡馆和沙龙并不完全不同，正如哈贝马斯所见，它们为公共领域提供了基础设施，”她写道。 （狡辩：她提到的 Jürgen Habermas 1962 年出版的《公共领域的结构转型》一书中描述的咖啡馆和沙龙文化是 17 世纪和 18 世纪的现象，而不是 19 世纪。）</p><p>但我们了解到，卡尔森女士实际上并没有去过她所写的枪支商店。她想“遵守大流行对研究、旅行和社交距离的限制”，因此只通过电话与受访者交谈。她试图将这种恶习转变为美德，但这一尝试并不令人信服（“远程访谈……有助于推进我自己对定性研究方法的思考”）。我的猜测是，这本书会受益于面对面的采访：她对枪支商店老板的描述充满了对他们的无情假设，以至于你想知道她是否期望学到任何东西。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-ec01d24e?mod=books_arts_lead_story" target="_blank" class="icon none">本周我们读的 14 本书</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-ec01d24e?mod=books_arts_lead_story"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828171?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p>第二修正案及其不满、奥古斯特·威尔逊的生活和戏剧、海洋深处的旅程等等。</p></div></div><p>在关于党派之争的一章中，她引用了“来自佛罗里达州的白人枪支卖家”杰克的言论，这是其中一个例子。杰克对政治导致他的家庭成员分裂这一事实感到遗憾。 “不幸的是，”他告诉卡尔森女士，“顽固的自由派不会与保守派沟通——即使我们从不谈论政治！ 。 。 。他们的意见取决于他们，我们仍然因此而爱他们——但他们的感觉不一样。我觉得这反映了这个国家今天的状况。”</p><p>因此，这位枪店老板的表现就像是在 21 世纪的美国可能会看到的一种跨党派感情的表达：“我们仍然爱他们。”不过，对于卡尔森女士来说，杰克是这里的党派人士，因为——现在明白了——他只将党派之争归咎于自由派。她在谈到杰克的观点时写道：“认为自由主义者、左派和民主党是思想封闭的精英主义者的假设，不仅使人们对他们的反感合法化，而且还表达了当代美国表面之下日益恶化的潜在政治、文化和经济焦虑。”政治。”卡尔森女士没有想到杰克对他的大家庭的描述是准确的，或者受过高等教育的自由主义者可能对典型的“来自佛罗里达州的白人枪支卖家”的看法比他对他们的看法更糟糕。</p><p>当然，在美国，这些以及所有其他有关枪支的争论的背后都是美国宪法第二修正案：“一支管理良好的民兵，对于自由国家的安全是必要的，人民有权持有和携带武器，不得侵犯。”罗杰·威廉姆斯大学法学教授卡尔·T·博格斯在《麦迪逊的民兵：第二修正案的隐藏历史》一书中指出，詹姆斯·麦迪逊起草修正案是为了满足南方奴隶主的要求，他们担心联邦政府会取缔州。民兵——他们抵御奴隶起义的最佳防御手段。</p><p>这本书是《加州大学戴维斯分校法律评论》1998 年一篇文章的扩展，提出了枪支辩论的一方会欣然接受的论点。但我的怀疑是在第 8 页提出的，作者承认他的论点依赖于间接证据，解释了什么是间接证据，什么不是，并声称这本书因为依赖它而“更有趣”。</p><p>博格斯先生的文章写得清晰而引人入胜，尽管快速阅读了最初的百页文章表明这​​本书并没有给他的论点实质内容增添太多内容。即使你同意，读一本完整的学术专着也需要读很多书才能获得如此有限的回报。</p><p>我不知道。该书的论点基于这样一种信念：在美国革命时代的政治阶层中，很少有人仍然相信常备军威胁着自由，因此需要民兵来捍卫自由。如果他们真的不再相信，正如波格斯先生所说，麦迪逊关于自由必须有一支训练有素的民兵的话就是虚言，是对奴隶主的安抚。但当时许多政治家称赞民兵是对抗暴政的堡垒，而博古斯先生坚持认为他们的话不真诚，这并不能令人信服。他的论文也没有解释，如果民兵如此过时，为什么马萨诸塞州和宾夕法尼亚州这两个对保护奴隶制没有兴趣的州却通过了保护民兵的宪法条款。</p><p>不难看出，这本书的要点是通过将第二修正案与奴隶制联系起来来诋毁第二修正案，从而抹黑第二修正案保障个人拥有枪支权利的论点。博格斯先生回避了第二修正案的法律解释这一棘手问题，但在书的最后一页，他暗示麦迪逊和他的同事会“震惊”，因为该修正案现在被认为允许个人拥有枪支。我能想到许多奇怪的、现在流行的对美国宪法的解释，这些解释会让开国元勋们感到震惊。那不是其中之一。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。斯威姆是《华尔街日报》的社论版撰稿人。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 04 Aug 2023 16:03:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ Three-books-on-the-second-amendment-a2c669e8</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ Three-books-on-the-second-amendment-a2c669e8<author><![CDATA[Barton Swaim]]></author><category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>凶杀案</category><category>社会问题</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>凶杀案</category><category>社会问题</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘August Wilson’ Review: Staging the Blues]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>这位剧作家对黑人生活和历史的胜利而令人心碎的描述超越了流派，改变了美国戏剧。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11490979256760064080404590112113650185570"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829333?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">奥古斯特·威尔逊.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Tom Sweeney/明尼阿波利斯明星论坛报/ZUMA/Alamy </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11490979256760064080404590112113650185570"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">艾萨克·巴特勒</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 4 日上午 11:46 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/august-wilson-review-staging-the-blues-d28ffa2a"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>如果没有奥古斯特·威尔逊，就无法想象美国文学，无论是戏剧文学还是其他文学。这位剧作家于 2005 年因肝癌去世，他改变了美国戏剧，并用黑人白话创作了一种新的抒情诗，其作品的雄心和广阔性可与沃尔特·惠特曼的作品相媲美。威尔逊的《20 世纪循环》——本世纪每十年一部剧，除了一部以外，所有剧都发生在他的家乡匹兹堡山区——从非裔美国人生活的细节中汲取力量。</p><p>在奥古斯特·威尔逊的一部戏剧中——就像他从中汲取灵感的罗马尔·比尔登拼贴画一样——小故事、歌曲、食谱、对爱、正义和理解的呼喊，暴力或调情的闪光，所有这些加起来就构成了某种不朽的东西。观看威尔逊作品的伟大制作，就是见证大迁徙，以及它所催生的美国黑人的经历，在他的人物的生活中上演，无论他们的胜利和心碎。</p><p>然而他最伟大的发明可能就是他自己。威尔逊自学成才，自取名字——他出生时叫弗雷德里克·基特尔，以一位他几乎不认识、也很少承认的白人父亲的名字命名——威尔逊是一位传奇的健谈家和臭名昭著的寓言家。他的伟大和他的自我创造都对未来的传记作家提出了巨大的挑战。你如何看穿威尔逊死后封圣和他对自己的生活不真实的习惯的双重迷雾，从而找到隐藏在其之下的真实人物？ </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/a27d9f09-87f7-4cea-919d-003cd669e9e7.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>那么，对我们所有人来说，幸运的是，我们拥有帕蒂·哈蒂根 (Patti Hartigan) 的杰作《奥古斯特·威尔逊：一生》(August Wilson: A Life)。凭借艰苦的研究、风格上的神韵以及既钦佩又严格的眼光，哈蒂根女士拼凑出了 20 世纪周期背后的人物，将威尔逊带入了激烈而复杂的生活。</p><p>威尔逊在他的戏剧中挖掘了家族传说，根据他所说的“血液的记忆”进行写作，因此哈蒂根女士的叙述的前几章读起来就像威尔逊角色会讲述的那种故事，这也许并不奇怪。她从威尔逊的祖母开始，以及与北卡罗来纳州乡村当地一位白人农民的禁忌关系，这个故事以暴力结束，最终将她的女儿黛西送到了北方的匹兹堡。在那里，黛西遇到了一位名叫弗雷德里克·基特尔的德国面包师。到 1941 年，他们成为了恋人，1945 年 4 月 27 日，黛西生下了他们的儿子小弗雷德里克·奥古斯特·基特尔 (Frederick August Kittel Jr.)。</p><p>作为一个小男孩，“弗雷迪”是一位狂热的读者和才华横溢的学生，但在 1960 年因被错误指控抄袭而辍学，转向当地图书馆寻找他了解世界所需的资料。他决定成为一名诗人，这让他的母亲非常懊恼，年轻时他做过一系列零工。哈蒂根女士报告说，与此同时，他会尽可能地写作，“在餐巾纸、收据和随意的纸片上记下想法”。由于与房东发生争执，他在监狱里呆了三天，晚上，一名囚犯独自在牢房里唱歌，他因此受到了布鲁斯的影响。 “他开始相信布鲁斯最充分地表达了黑人生活，”哈蒂根女士写道，“这种音乐对他后来的戏剧产生了不可磨灭的影响。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-ec01d24e?mod=books_arts_lead_story" target="_blank" class="icon none">本周我们读的 14 本书</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-ec01d24e?mod=books_arts_lead_story"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828171?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p>第二修正案及其不满、奥古斯特·威尔逊的生活和戏剧、海洋深处的旅程等等。</p></div></div><p>布鲁斯成为威尔逊“四个B”中的第一个，这些影响塑造了他的生活和工作。其他人是罗马尔·比尔登（Romare Bearden），他的作品为艺术如何呈现黑人的日常生活树立了标准；阿米里·巴拉卡（Amiri Baraka）对黑人艺术自决的坚持巩固了威尔逊的道德观；还有豪尔赫·路易斯·博尔赫斯，他的正式实验向威尔逊证明，作家可以开辟自己的美学道路。未经正规训练，他于 1968 年作为匹兹堡黑色地平线剧院的创始人之一开始担任导演。很快他也开始写剧本，1982年他的剧本《马·雷尼的黑屁股》被尤金·奥尼尔剧作家会议接受，其艺术总监劳埃德·理查兹成为威尔逊的拥护者和导演。</p><p>从那时起，正如哈蒂根女士以强烈的戏剧感记录的那样，威尔逊进行了激烈的斗争，首先是为了自己的尊严，然后是为了控制自己的工作，最后是为了完成他的周期。这场战斗最终耗尽了威尔逊和理查兹的合作关系，威尔逊的十部戏剧中有六部是由这对搭档诞生的，威尔逊赢得了两项普利策奖，并使他家喻户晓。这也将严重考验他的许多人际关系。所有伟大的艺术家都在努力成为配得上他们想要创造的艺术的人，而威尔逊为自己设定的使命因他的过程而变得更加困难，他的过程同样是椭圆形的、混乱的和苛刻的。他通过倾听角色的声音来写作，询问他们有关他们的生活以及他们如何走到现在的位置的问题，然后写下结果。他的早期草稿通常是一系列勉强串联起来的独白，重大情节事件缺失或解释不充分。他需要多个完整的舞台作品来理解他的戏剧并将其塑造成最终形式。</p><p>但是哦，他变出了什么样的最终形态啊！二十世纪周期围绕着一系列相互关联的主题和主题——黑人工人阶级生活的日常细节、忧郁、暴力的幽灵、白人至上的台下压力、将自己的生活植根于历史的重要性——穿越多种流派。 《栅栏》是一部厨房水槽现实主义作品，为他赢得了第一个普利策奖。 《钢琴课》是一个鬼故事，为他赢得了第二次机会。 《七把吉他》是一部悬疑谋杀案，而《乔·特纳的来去匆匆》是他神秘的、不断重读的杰作，是一部魔幻现实主义的史诗作品。</p><p>威尔逊经常住在酒店外面，结过三次婚。他拖延、抽烟、沉迷于女性，并且错过了对孩子的大部分教育。他的成功使他与匹兹堡原来的社区疏远到了如此程度，以至于他被特别要求不要在他儿时最好的朋友之一罗布·彭尼的葬礼上发言。威尔逊还必须面对自己的身份：一位美国黑人剧作家，被一个以白人为主的机构指定为整个种族代言和代表。这个角色可能对他的钱包有利，但这也使他处于一个不可能的境地，并使他成为同侪的目标，他们对他在白人机构中的成功越来越怀疑。他最终选择在题为“我站立的基础”的挑衅性演讲中向该机构坦诚对话。 （全面披露：哈蒂根女士的书中引用了我对这一争议的一些报道。）</p><p>所有这些以及更多内容都在《奥古斯特·威尔逊：一生》中得到了精彩的叙述——这一壮举在没有威尔逊庄园合作的情况下制作，更加令人印象深刻。哈蒂根女士注重完美、有说服力的细节。 Thus Wilson&#39;s one significant memory of his father is of a trip to a shoe store where “Kittel handed Freddy a handful of coins and told him to jingle them in his pocket, to make it look as if he had money to spare,” while his amanuensis Todd Kreidler is shaped by “a chilly relationship with his father, a used-car salesman who did not seem to know the phone number to his emotions.” She isn&#39;t afraid to take Wilson&#39;s work to task, particularly in its portrayals of women, while also recognizing the unique power of his gifts. Ms. Hartigan also unearths plenty of juicy backstage gossip. Her chapters on the sturm und drang surrounding “Fences,” and star James Earl Jones&#39;s attempts to use producer Carole Shorenstein Hays to get Wilson to rewrite the play to be more traditional and amenable to white audiences, are equally shocking and thrilling.</p><p> Reacting to Wilson&#39;s death, the playwright Tony Kushner told the New York Times: “Heroic is not a word one uses often without embarrassment to describe a writer or playwright, but the diligence and ferocity of effort behind the creation of his body of work is really an epic story.” Finally, with “August Wilson: A Life,” we have an epic account to match.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。 Butler is the author of “The Method: How the Twentieth Century Learned to Act.”</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 04 Aug 2023 15:46:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/august-wilson-review-staging-the-blues-d28ffa2a</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/august-wilson-review-staging-the-blues-d28ffa2a<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Fiction: ‘The Brothers Karamazov’]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> In a new translation, Dostoyevsky&#39;s magnum opus emerges as a singular portrait of apocalyptic spiritual crisis. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11221797970291203701404590128440676207142"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829534?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> &#39;Before the Confession&#39; (1879-85) by Ilya Repin.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Bridgeman Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11221797970291203701404590128440676207142"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sam-sacks" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sam Sacks</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 4, 2023 11:41 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fiction-the-brothers-karamazov-4776b0b1"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Here&#39;s a data point that may be useful in the tricky task of choosing between excellent translations of a Russian classic: In Constance Garnett&#39;s canonical 1912 version of Fyodor Dostoyevsky&#39;s “The Brothers Karamazov,” the word “ecstasy” and its variations (“ecstatic,” “ecstatically”) appear 34 times. In Michael R. Katz&#39;s new translation, published in a solid brick of a hardcover, the words show up 78 times, more than double the frequency. There&#39;s a lesson in the numbers. Garnett&#39;s brilliance was bound up in the fluency of her prose, and she was prone to taking Dostoyevsky in hand when he became too crazed or inscrutable, fixing repetitions, cutting apparent non sequiturs and breaking up massive paragraphs into shorter, more readable portions. Mr. Katz has accepted ungainliness in return for greater intensity. His translation sharpens the sensation unique to Dostoyevsky, that of a man clutching your forearm and shouting something into your face. It feels truly manic—though the better word surely is “ecstatic.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/29be3255-c58b-4418-bde7-2774c81994f3.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Dostoyevsky, we now know, was afflicted with a rare form of epilepsy in which he experienced “ecstatic auras”—joyous, mystical presentiments—in the moments before falling into a seizure. “For a few brief instants I feel a happiness unthinkable in the normal state and unimaginable for anyone who hasn&#39;t experienced it,” he said of his condition. The diagnostic mixture of bliss and terror may well be unimaginable, yet it was precisely what his writing evoked, and to no small extent the symptomatology of his illness reads like a summation of his greatest books: the nervous agitation; the sense of overload that brings about vertiginous levels of awareness; the strange dilation of time; the brief apprehension of some engulfing, epiphanic truth, followed by a shattering collapse into disorder.</p><p> Mr. Katz has already produced spiky, vibrant translations of “Notes From Underground,” “Devils” and “Crime and Punishment,” and with “The Brothers Karamazov” he takes on Dostoyevsky&#39;s uncontested magnum opus, completed in 1880 just a few months before the author&#39;s death at 59. (Dostoyevsky, a chain smoker, died from emphysema, but if any book was going to kill him it&#39;s this one.) As was often the case in his novels, a wire-thin plot holds everything together. Here it&#39;s the murder of the wicked old landowner Fyodor Pavlovich Karamazov and the subsequent trial of the alleged killer, his eldest son, Dmitry. But behind the “external side” of the book are secondary stories of love and death, sermons, theological debates, anguished monologues, fever dreams and philosophical parables, including “The Grand Inquisitor,” among the most renowned chapters in Western literature.</p><p> The brothers&#39; contradictory personalities allow for such scope. Central to everything is the novel&#39;s hero, the saintly Alyosha, who has been living in a monastery under the guidance of Father Zosima and who acts as a kind of confessor to the many people doing their utmost to destroy one another and themselves. Dmitry, a drunken, debt-ridden carouser, is the most openly sinful of the brothers, but his candor makes him curiously endearing. (“Though I&#39;m a man of vile desires, I&#39;m honest,” he swears, and it seems to be true.) One suspects Dostoyevsky is harsher with Ivan Karamazov, the tormented intellectual who wields reason against faith and morality, because he&#39;s the most autobiographical. Then there&#39;s the enigmatic Smerdyakov, Fyodor Pavlovich&#39;s illegitimate son and servant, who rarely speaks but is always hanging around and observing. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-ec01d24e?mod=books_arts_lead_story" target="_blank" class="icon none">14 Books We Read This Week</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"> <a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-ec01d24e?mod=books_arts_lead_story"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828171?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p> The Second Amendment and its discontents, the life and drama of August Wilson, journeys to the ocean&#39;s depths and more.</p></div></div><p> With these and other figures Dostoyevsky spins a dense web of feuds, which are triggered by various pretexts—usually women or money—but are really propelled by psychological oneupmanship, the deep-seated desire to hold power in every relationship. Only Alyosha is exempt from the fighting because he freely begs for and dispenses forgiveness whenever conflict arises. His enthusiastic submission to Christ is both a beautiful and a disturbing example, and it causes those near him to turn their antagonisms inward, so that they&#39;re ultimately warring against their own nature. There are occasional tone shifts in this long book—Dostoyevsky can be quite funny, especially when depicting daily Russian life—but the dominant mood is apocalyptic spiritual crisis. The novel works itself into an emotional frenzy and somehow sustains that heightened condition for hundreds of pages, impossibly poised on the threshold of either salvation or damnation.</p><p> Dostoyevsky&#39;s willingness to convincingly portray the allure of both fates is what makes “The Brothers Karamazov” a work of art rather than a singular religious tract. Father Zosima requires Alyosha to leave the monastery and “sojourn in the world,” living among people for whom depravity can access a feeling closely akin to religious exaltation. In the novel&#39;s most moving scene, Alyosha is overcome by a vision of God&#39;s infinite mercy and he drops to the ground, “weeping, sobbing, watering the earth with his tears, vowing ecstatically to love it, love it forever and ever.” Yet the scene is followed by a virtuoso section depicting the deranged, blood-spattered bacchanal Dmitry throws the night his father is killed, and it too lifts him into an “ecstatic state” of perception, though its consummations are outrageous vices.</p><p> Where does the reader fit in all this? Discussing Dmitry&#39;s trial, which becomes notorious throughout Russia, a troubled acquaintance of Alyosha says, “Everyone loves the fact that he killed his father. 。 。 。 Everyone says it&#39;s dreadful, but on their own, they love it terribly. I&#39;m the first one who does.” The novel might condemn this hypocrisy if not for the fact that it depends upon it for its narrative to be effective. Dostoyevsky makes us voyeurs to a ghastly murder mystery, arousing us to the same “feverish, irritating interest” by the question of who killed Fyodor Pavlovich as the gossipy court spectators.</p><p> Because what matters is, whether by means noble or base, that we, too, are made to feel the terrible internal pressure that throttles the characters. Like no other book, “The Brothers Karamazov” describes and drags its readers to a state of unbearable tension. It is only there, at the breaking point, that moments of clarity become possible, and those moments are what can save us.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 04 Aug 2023 15:41:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/fiction-the-brothers-karamazov-4776b0b1</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/fiction-the-brothers-karamazov-4776b0b1<author><![CDATA[Sam Sacks]]></author><category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Life Sculpted’ Review: What’s Eating Our Planet?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The Earth is full of bioeroders. Most are humble things like bivalves—but given enough time, even the barnacle can be the tool of an island&#39;s demise. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11754030163052123715304590115993574748492"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829055?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A crinoid fossil.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Kevin Schafer/Alamy </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11754030163052123715304590115993574748492"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Eugenia Bone</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 4, 2023 11:34 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/life-sculpted-review-whats-eating-our-planet-5d2f750a"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Dinosaur bones have never turned me on the way fossilized footprints, nests, burrows and poop do. Skeletons are static. But dinosaur tracks jumpstart my imagination and suddenly I&#39;m visualizing the creatures meandering, running, stalking prey, herding offspring. Tracks are the traces of living.</p><p> It is often said that life changes the environment. But after reading Anthony Martin&#39;s “Life Sculpted: Tales of the Animals, Plants, and Fungi That Drill, Break, and Scrape to Shape the Earth,” it seems more accurate to say that <em>living</em> changes the environment. It was true of the dinosaur era, and it remains true today. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><p> <strong>Life Sculpted</strong></p><p> <em>By Anthony J. Martin</em></p><p> <em>Chicago, 369 pages, $27.50</em> </p></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/c2979cff-5b12-41f5-883e-9a9a512e0c25.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Ichnology is the study of animal activity in sediments and rock—specifically, the identification of fossilized tracks, burrows and excavations—and how those actions disturbed landscapes. Ichnologists hypothesize about the behavior of ancient organisms by examining the fossilized remains of their actions and comparing them to the remains of modern descendants. An ichnologist like Mr. Martin can look at a slab of Cretaceous rock and, where I see shallow indentations, he sees a fish feeding pit—because he&#39;s seen similar feeding pits made by contemporary stingrays. A fossilized coral riddled with holes? Mr. Martin sees evidence of burrowing clams because, well, burrowing clams are still at it. “Life Sculpted” is a feast of such examples; maybe more than the average reader needs to get the point: that species come and go, but ways of surviving endure.</p><p> Mr. Martin, a professor at Emory University, is the author of numerous books and the co-discoverer of the first-known burrowing dinosaur, a fact both obvious (why <em>wouldn&#39;t</em> a dinosaur burrow for the same reasons of temperature regulation and protection that other animals do?) and amazing (dinosaurs burrowed like other animals do?!). “Life Sculpted” is the sequel to “The Evolution Underground,” Mr. Martin&#39;s 2017 book on how burrows and burrowing animals changed landscapes and helped some lineages of animals survive extinction and general environmental mayhem. I loved the tales of nasty alligator burrows, fiddler crab copulation chambers and giant sloth dens.</p><p> “Life Sculpted” deals with bioerosion. When I think about erosion I usually think about weather: the persistent pressure of wind, water and temperature on rock, bone and shell. But biology plays a role, too. Earth is populated by bioeroders, critters who nibble away at the hard parts of our world and release essential nutrients, like phosphorous, back into the system. These nibblers aren&#39;t the most charismatic of organisms—they are mainly humble things like bivalves—but given enough time, a barnacle can be the tool of an island&#39;s demise.</p><p> Mr. Martin introduces us to these creatures, both ancient and contemporary, starting with tiny cyanobacteria that degrade limestone and clamshells. Larger borers include lichens—symbiotic organisms composed of mutually dependent parts: a fungus and photosynthetic bacteria or algae—which over their thousand-year lifetimes slowly crumble fresh rock into rubble, the fungal partner mining for essential minerals, causing a kind of osteoporosis of stone. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-ec01d24e?mod=books_arts_lead_story" target="_blank" class="icon none">14 Books We Read This Week</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"> <a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-ec01d24e?mod=books_arts_lead_story"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828171?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p> The Second Amendment and its discontents, the life and drama of August Wilson, journeys to the ocean&#39;s depths and more.</p></div></div><p> For readers who are fascinated by living fossils such as bryozoans and horseshoe crabs, there is much to love between this book&#39;s covers. I am now captivated by the enigmatic chiton—an ancient model of life with no discernible front or back—that sticks to marine rocks and scrapes them away, bit by bit, in search of algae.</p><p> Bioerosion is particularly evident in the tropics. Thanks to chewing invertebrates, the rocky coast of the Bahamas is diminishing by about a nickel&#39;s thickness every year. And those beautiful Bahaman white-sand beaches? They are the result of bioerosion, too. Parrotfish consume coral in search of the photosynthetic partners that live there, and poop out that marvelous fine sand. Which means the beaches that have launched a thousand honeymoon videos have passed through a parrotfish&#39;s digestive system at least once.</p><p> Much of the book deals with creatures that break down bones, wood or shells, including the moon snail, the “lion of the tidal flats.” I know this animal intimately. When I was a child vacationing with my family in Cape Cod, I would follow the snail trails in the sand; as I dug them up with my foot, the huge snail would slowly wrap its slimy self, disgusting and meltingly yummy, around my small toes. Turns out they prowl the sand for unsuspecting clams, into whose shells they drill a hole and suck the insides out—a most disturbing way to go.</p><p> “Life Sculpted” ranges widely, from eroders of different sediments to eroders of whale bones and ship hulls; it even digresses into the forces of shark, alligator and T-Rex bites, all of which shatter bones. The book explores the tools animals use to erode hard materials: Seagulls drop clams onto stones to bust them open; sea otters slam clams with rocks while floating on water; capuchin monkeys use rocks to crack nuts, eroding both the shells and the rock tools. And, of course, early humans used rocks to break bones for the nutrient-rich marrow inside. Finding the right rock to do a particular bioerosion job led to mining, the way we erode landscapes now.</p><p> Style-wise, Mr. Martin&#39;s writing contains many of the same tropes as other scientists-turned-writers, like jocular chapter headings that imply more lightness than is to be found therein, and punning. (“Life is hard, but when it comes to evolution, life overcame by being boring.”) Also, the queasy cultural reference: “Putting mushrooms between bell peppers and broccoli and calling them &#39;vegetables&#39; is as inappropriate as seating Banksy between Frida Kahlo and Diego Rivera at a dinner party and introducing all three as artists.” I think the Riveras would have loved Banksy, at least for his politics.</p><p> Less avoidable, perhaps, is the use of scientific jargon. Witty asides don&#39;t make new concepts easier to retain. Many science writers (myself included) often don&#39;t realize they can safely trim and simplify their material and popular audiences will still walk away with about as much. But even though I sometimes felt bogged down by dense scientific description, there are many eureka moments in “Life Sculpted”—and some truly beautiful ones.</p><p> Mr. Martin describes prehistoric (and contemporary) crinoids, also known as sea lilies. They resemble plants with roots, stems and flowers, but upon closer inspection are made of calcite plates. “Crinoids are not just animals,” the author tells us, “but exquisite creatures that implore you to weep with joy that such complexity and splendor has existed for so long on this earth.” An animal that looks like a plant? I am now a little obsessed with crinoids, too.</p><p> The key takeaway of “Life Sculpted,” and ichnology more generally, is that geology is indistinguishable from biology. A prevailing theme in popular culture these days is that all life is connected. But what Mr. Martin implies is that it is not only biotic organisms that are interdependent, but the geological and chemical systems of the planet, too. And while the gap between the biotic and abiotic worlds may seem huge, it&#39;s the science that&#39;s complicated. So, while “Life Sculpted” is not everybody&#39;s idea of beach reading, think of it this way: It&#39;s the beach.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -多发性硬化症。 Bone is a writer on science and food. Her next book, on psychoactive mushrooms, will be published next year.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 04 Aug 2023 15:34:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/life-sculpted-review-whats-eating-our-planet-5d2f750a</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/life-sculpted-review-whats-eating-our-planet-5d2f750a<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The Underworld’ Review: Life in the Oceanic Abyss]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Journeying to the depths of the ocean reveals its beauty, terror, precarity—and infinite mystery. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11221797970291203701404590124131779772218"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830069?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> *** ONE-TIME USE *** A gaggle of rattails and two assfish investigate bait in an image captured by the Caladan Oceanic Five Deeps Expedition.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Tamara Stubbs/Atlantic Productions/Discovery </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11221797970291203701404590124131779772218"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">David P. Barash</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 4, 2023 11:29 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-underworld-review-life-in-the-oceanic-abyss-28727ade"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> It is said that we know more about the surface of the moon than about the depths of the ocean. That might not be the case for Susan Casey. Across an eventful career Ms. Casey—a former editor in chief of O, the Oprah Magazine—has researched and written books about big waves, great white sharks, dolphins and, in “The Underworld,” the oceanic depths. She dedicates her latest book to “those who love the ocean,” which she clearly does, writing about it with passion, knowledge and insights from personal experience. To read “The Underworld” is to travel in and about manned submersibles capable of going where no one has gone before—down to the hadal zone, which bottoms out at 36,000 feet, where pressures are so great it feels like being stomped on by the equivalent of 292 fully loaded 747s stacked on top of you.</p><p> Darwin, suffering five years of seasickness while voyaging on the Beagle, concluded that the ocean was “a tedious waste.” Unusually for him, in this case he was wrong. After an engaging introduction to the history of sea-monster lore and 19th-century efforts at deep-sea dredging, Ms. Casey gets down to business. Deep down. And with abundant obeisance to “the deep&#39;s imprimatur of weirdness,” she seconds Captain Nemo, from Jules Verne&#39;s “Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea,” who proclaimed that “the sea is the medium which supports the most fantastic, prodigious forms of existence.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/99672684-d904-40d9-be00-badbbf8bf9e0.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> We encounter the appropriately named “weirdfish”—“a shockingly ugly fish with a bulbous head, spiky teeth, a Quasimodo hump on its back, and a diaphanous, eel-shaped body.” There are tubeworms, denizens of deep-sea vents, that have “no eyes, no mouth, no gut, no anus—which would seem like a raw deal for any animal.” But they thrive, absorbing bacteria through their skin. Moreover, in addition to giant squid, there&#39;s strong evidence for a “colossal squid” and maybe even a supercolossal species. Here&#39;s hoping.</p><p> Ms. Casey&#39;s writing takes us to pulsating undersea vents, notably in the Pacific, including black smokers, which are superhot (around 700 degrees Fahrenheit) and constantly belch metal sulfides, creating chimneys that can be nearly 200 feet tall. These vents create unique and bizarre ecosystems, a “creeping crawling carnival,” that includes “microbes that can reside way down in the pores and fissures of the ocean crust—in extreme temperatures, under annihilating pressures, and subsisting on toxic chemicals.” Deep-sea vents possibly resemble the crucibles where life originated, she writes: “a <em>Star Wars</em> bar-scene ecosystem.”</p><p> Not just a knowledgeable guide, Ms. Casey is also a memorable wordsmith: “Mantle rock is solid, but it behaves like angry Silly Putty,” she writes. “When dragged from its deep womb . 。 。 it throws off heat, hydrogen, and methane in a kind of planetary hissy fit. You can&#39;t accuse it of being dull.” Ms. Casey revels in the deep ocean&#39;s “pulsing lights and phantasmagoric shapes and jewel colors.” So does the reader. Deep off the Hawaiian Islands, “sometimes a false cat shark would swish by like a runway model,” she writes, “sporting the elongated eyes of a gray alien and a wide jack-o&#39;-lantern grin.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-ec01d24e?mod=books_arts_lead_story" target="_blank" class="icon none">14 Books We Read This Week</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"> <a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-ec01d24e?mod=books_arts_lead_story"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828171?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p> The Second Amendment and its discontents, the life and drama of August Wilson, journeys to the ocean&#39;s depths and more.</p></div></div><p> On occasion, her reveries are memorable prose-poems. “In the abyss,” she writes, “you don&#39;t glimpse the mystery—you <em>enter</em> it, and your consciousness is the only fixed point. Subtract time and you&#39;re left with presence. In the deep, you lose your bearings and you find yourself.” Given the intense first-person component of this book, a reader might wonder if Ms. Casey got to make any deep dives herself, in addition to reporting on them. She did.</p><p> In its second half, however, “The Underworld” takes on water, losing some of its <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TCLRY" class="company-name">Technicolor</a> mojo as Ms. Casey recounts the biographies and adventures of her current deep-sea aquanaut heroes, some of whom seem, to this reader, engaged primarily in showboating ego trips. It&#39;s hard to read “The Underworld” and not think about the recent media frenzy that attended the death of five persons aboard a deep-sea submersible aiming to visit the remains of the Titanic. That tragedy involving undersea tourists, however, should not overshadow the intrinsic importance and fascination of research and exploration in the deep ocean environment.</p><p> Ms. Casey&#39;s book has more than enough deep-sea biology and geology to dazzle. Did you know that bristlemouths (a fish) are the most abundant vertebrates on earth? For every living human, there are a hundred thousand bristlemouths. And many, perhaps most, deep-sea fish “appear frightful, even terrifying—straight from nightmare central casting. Some look like disembodied heads; others are all teeth. The viperfish&#39;s fangs are so long they burst out of its mouth and start to wrap around its face.” There&#39;s also the stoplight loosejaw dragonfish—whose name provides all the description needed.</p><p> Ms. Casey does not hide her heartsick feeling that this extraordinary (and still largely unknown) deep ocean is at risk from plastics and other pollutants, as well as from planned ocean-floor strip mining, an environmentally destructive blunder that the author passionately argues we should avoid.</p><p> There may or may not be extraterrestrial aliens “out there” in space, which we may or may not encounter. But there are definitely lots of aliens on earth, inhabiting the depths of our mostly watery world—which are also, Ms. Casey emphasizes, key to human flourishing and survival: “The deep,” she writes, “buffers our excess carbon (at least so far), drives the ocean&#39;s circulation (and thus, climate), regulates the earth&#39;s geochemistry (important, to put it mildly), and absorbs surplus heat (ditto)—to cite just a few of its services. Humming away in obscurity, it&#39;s the foundation of the planet.”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。 Barash is professor emeritus of psychology at the University of Washington and the author, most recently, of “Oops! The Worst Blunders of All Time, From Pandora&#39;s Box to Putin&#39;s War.”</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 04 Aug 2023 15:29:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-underworld-review-life-in-the-oceanic-abyss-28727ade</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-underworld-review-life-in-the-oceanic-abyss-28727ade<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Two Books on Peter Beard]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> On the job, the wildlife photographer was once gored by an elephant. During off-hours, he gained notoriety for his commitment to partying and publicity. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590124131293177618"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829073?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Peter Beard&#39;s studio at Hog Ranch, in Kenya.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Hakan Ludwigson </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590124131293177618"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Dominic Green</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 4, 2023 11:24 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/two-books-on-peter-beard-cfc2a4ac"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Peter Beard photographed supermodels and African animals and took elephantine quantities of cocaine in nightclubs. He said his life was his art. Beard was casual with his camera, but he took his drug use very seriously. A child of family money who never worked too hard, he died in 2020 at 82, after wandering into the woods near his Montauk, NY, home. He had suffered three strokes and had developed dementia, cancer and heart trouble. He left his heart pills on the bedside table. Beard, who had been gored by an elephant in 1996, died like an old tusker going to the elephants&#39; graveyard.</p><p> Charming, glamorous and as coldly manipulative as Patricia Highsmith&#39;s talented Mr. Ripley, Beard makes a great subject for a biography—or two. Christopher Wallace&#39;s <strong>“Twentieth-Century Man” (Ecco, 272 pages, $32.99)</strong> usually chooses the legend over the life and the life over the art. Graham Boynton&#39;s <strong>“Wild” (St. Martin&#39;s, 344 pages, $35)</strong> , published last year, is a thoughtful and well-researched exploration of how the art emerged from the life, and makes the uphill case that Beard was a significant artist. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/95851aa3-7f93-4017-82b3-5ff44397d635.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Born in 1938, Beard was the great-grandson of the railroad tycoon James J. Hill. Beard&#39;s paternal grandmother, Ruth, married the lawyer Anson McCook Beard II. When he died, she married the tobacco heir Pierre Lorillard V, and later, moving “from cigarettes to champagne,” as family lore had it, she wed Emile Heidsieck. Anson III, Ruth&#39;s son from her first marriage, married Peter&#39;s mother, Roseanne.</p><p> Peter&#39;s elder brother, Anson IV, called their father “the ultimate WASC—White Anglo-Saxon Catholic.” Anson III was a member of “the lucky sperm club” who “enjoyed a life of total entitlement,” managed the family money and drank a lot. Anson IV became, in the words of the New York Times, a “titan of Wall Street.” Peter became a titanic irritant to his mother and took it out on all the women he seduced. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/0e5fefa6-bd00-40f5-8c99-009be487969d.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> “Mummy&#39;s greatest disappointment was her love-hate relationship with Peter,” Anson IV recorded for posterity. Anson IV, who might have been a novelist in the line of Louis Auchincloss, recalls that his mother beat him “so hard one time that she broke my father&#39;s DKE fraternity paddle on my backside.” The parents objected when Granny Virginia, Roseanne&#39;s mother, gave Peter a camera: They thought he would break it or lose it. Instead, he found a way of life, and an agreeable way of seeing the world: one-eyed and controlling.</p><p> Miseducated at boarding schools in New England and old, Beard fantasized about the colonial world of Karen Blixen&#39;s 1937 memoir “Out of Africa” even before he met Quentin Keynes. A great-grandson of Charles Darwin and the nephew of the economist John Maynard Keynes, Quentin was in the habit of touring schools, showing films of his African safaris to the students and recruiting promising boys as camera bearers. In 1955, the 17-year-old Beard joined the 34-year-old Keynes on a trip through southern Africa and then north to Kenya.</p><p> Five years later, while enrolled at Yale, Beard returned to Kenya, which was still a British colony. Beard apprenticed himself to its old white hunters and modeled himself on Blixen&#39;s English lover, Denys Finch Hatton. Colonial-era hunters had massacred Kenya&#39;s big game, and the British authorities had jammed the survivors into reserves bordered by a growing African population. In 1965 the 27-year-old Beard published “The End of the Game.” He predicted that a further rise in Africa&#39;s population would seal the fate of its wildlife. Beard was on the side of the fauna, not the people. He was prone to musings on how Hitler had discredited eugenics and saw epidemics as nature&#39;s answer to overpopulation.</p><p> “The End of the Game,” Mr. Boynton writes, elevated Beard from “trust fund roustabout to prophetic, if doom-laden, conservationist.” He bought a spread outside Kenya&#39;s capital, Nairobi, and married Mary “Minnie” Cushing, whose family had a mansion in Newport, RI Cushing turned out to be an even freer spirit than Beard and left him for the producer of the musical “Hair.” Beard attempted suicide, and then, as Mr. Wallace puts it, “swore never again to spend a single solitary second in his subconscious.” This did not stop him from exposing others to its contents. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-ec01d24e?mod=books_arts_lead_story" target="_blank" class="icon none">14 Books We Read This Week</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"> <a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-ec01d24e?mod=books_arts_lead_story"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828171?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p> The Second Amendment and its discontents, the life and drama of August Wilson, journeys to the ocean&#39;s depths and more.</p></div></div><p> In 1969 Beard was sentenced to a Kenyan jail after allegedly tying an African trespasser to a tree; he was freed after Jackie Onassis pulled strings via the American ambassador. In 1971 he published his most powerful images: The elephant population of Kenya&#39;s Tsavo National Park had stripped the reserve&#39;s vegetation and was now undergoing a Malthusian collapse. Beard&#39;s aerial photographs of the die-off evoke images of warfare and ecological collapse. Mass extinction, Mr. Wallace writes, was “the obsession of his life.” Beard said that the future was “black, dark, horrifying <em>black</em> totalitarianism.”</p><p> Though we have not followed the elephants into the graveyard, the class into which Beard was born was losing its power. Surviving like the fittest, Beard climbed up the new celebrity class and embraced what Mr. Wallace terms a demanding routine of “fashion shoots and safaris and debauchery.” He might have become a major environmentalist. Instead, he unfulfilled his potential as a jester for the talentless rich, a trophy hunter who provocatively posed gaunt models with giant elephant tusks.</p><p> Beard partied with the Rolling Stones and Truman Capote. He slept with Princess Lee Radziwill and models much younger than himself. He recorded monologues with Andy Warhol and got drunk with Francis Bacon. He was handsome and funny, but repartee ages about as well as oysters. Beard held his 40th birthday at Studio 54. He gave away his photographs to pay dental bills and drug dealers. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829477?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Beard at Hog Ranch.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Hakan Ludwigson</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Mr. Wallace calls Beard “a man of action, maybe the last great romantic adventurer.” Mr. Boynton calls him “clearly sociopathic.” He once took a rock and bludgeoned to death a cat belonging to his neighbor, Richard Avedon, because the creature annoyed him. “He liked the beauty of women and he liked to spin the web, and then he would walk away once he had ensnared you,” his second wife, the model Cheryl Tiegs, reflects. When Ms. Tiegs was pregnant, Beard hit her in the stomach, likely causing her miscarriage. Mr. Wallace omits to mention the young woman who told Mr. Boynton that Beard was “sexually violent” and “truly sadistic,” and that she needed antibiotics after he bit her all over her body.</p><p> Beard&#39;s first two wives and mothers-in-law might have dreamed of doing what the matriarch of an elephant herd did to him in 1996. She charged, headbutted Beard as he ran away, then smashed his pelvis, gored his thigh and repeatedly tried to crush him. Anson IV paid for Peter&#39;s repatriation and treatment. A show was arranged for him in Paris not long after the mauling. Though still addicted to publicity, he was never the same again.</p><p> As Anson IV said, Peter “never really managed to be interested that much in the well-being of others.” That is a rare understatement about a man who lived in overstatement. As each of these biographies shows in its way, Beard&#39;s photographs were eclipsed by his image, and his art by his life.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。 Green is a Journal contributor and a fellow of the Royal Historical Society.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 04 Aug 2023 15:24:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/two-books-on-peter-beard-cfc2a4ac</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/two-books-on-peter-beard-cfc2a4ac<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item></channel></rss>